        <p class="lead">we thought so</p>
        <div class="accordion" id="accordion2">
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseOne">
                        Why are you doing this?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-body collapse in">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        We love Japan; we love Bitcoin.  Unfortunately, unless you have a Japanese bank account - it is
                        hard to turn your coins into yen while you visit.  We are simply introducing a service that makes it easier
                        for you to use your bitcoins
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseTwo">
                        Are you a money transmitter?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-body collapse">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        In short: NO, we are not a money transmitter.  That sounds to us that you think we are in the USA.
                        We are not.  California has challenged Bitcoin Foundation as to whether they are a money transmitter ... the result
                        is a letter (Source <a href="http://www.scribd.com/doc/151346841/Bitcoin-Foundation-Response-to-California-DFI">here </a>)
                        which explains the background of a business that can be considered a money transmitter.  We do not even qualify as a money
                        transmitter because debit cards (the closest analogy we can use) are not considered "currency" under CA law.  Nor are Rakuten
                        points, or Amazon points.  Suica and Passmo cards are intended for tourists to Japan and have zero use anywhere in the world.

                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#cantigetone">
                        Can't I just get my own digital cash card when I visit?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="cantigetone" class="accordion-body collapse">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        Umm ... Absolutely!!! But then you will be working solely with fiat currency and waiting in line at currency exchange kiosks.
                        You also have to use the Japanese card issuing machines (here is an <a href="http://bit.ly/1e3laDy">example</a> ) Have fun in line :)
                    </div>
                </div>
        </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#creditcard">
                        Can't I just use my credit card?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="creditcard" class="accordion-body collapse">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        Yes and no.  Many Japanese stores do not accept credit cards.  You also cannot use credit card for normal train tickets.
                        Otherwise, go for it and use credit.  Suimo is not Meant to replace your credit card.
                        Suimo is meant for small purchases around small stores, train stations, etc. for everyday minor purchases..
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#runout">
                        What if I ran out of money on my cash card?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="runout" class="accordion-body collapse">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        You can add more money to the card at any train station if you have physical cash with you.  Hope you brought
                        some cash.  Here is how to recharge your card: <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GDCvwxHO-JU">
                        http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GDCvwxHO-JU
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#didnotuse">
                        What if I did not use all my money on the card ?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="didnotuse" class="accordion-body collapse">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        Send it back and we will refund via bitcoin anything you did not use (we will send you a self-addresses envelope)
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#refundprocess">
                        How does the refund process work?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="refundprocess" class="accordion-body collapse">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        Together with your purchase order you will receive a ***non paid*** self addressesed envelope.
                        Mail the card back to us either from Japan or from your home country (we recommend from Japan since domestic
                        postage is cheaper).  We send you ¥500+balance on the card via bitcoin to the BTC address listed on your profile.
                        Please note that we will refund <b>up to </b> the amount you originally put on the card.  Simple!
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#whypay">
                        Why do I have to pay ¥1000 overhead per card?
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div id="whypay" class="accordion-body collapse">
                    <div class="accordion-inner">
                        To buy a single Suica or Passmo card - costs ¥500 in Japan.  Consider it a deposit that you will get back.
                        The additional ¥500 is used for shipment costs, processing costs, and supplies.  When the card is returned,
                        the money is refunded.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
                <div class="accordion-heading">
                    <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#shadybusiness">
